Hey, I'm working on an embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU and I've run into a serious issue. The system has a slow memory leak that only shows up after about 4-6 hours of continuous operation. It's not crashing immediately, just gradually exhausting the heap until the watchdog triggers a reset.

Here is the core loop where we handle sensor data processing:

```cpp
void process_sensor_data(const SensorPacket* packet) {
    if (packet == nullptr) return;

    // Allocate buffer for processing
    uint8_t* processing_buffer = new uint8_t[packet->size];

    // Copy data
    std::memcpy(processing_buffer, packet->data, packet->size);

    // Perform complex DSP operations
    apply_filter(processing_buffer, packet->size);
    validate_checksum(processing_buffer, packet->size);

    // Data is sent to the telemetry module
    telemetry_module.send(processing_buffer, packet->size);

    // TODO: Free buffer? 
    // I thought I handled this in the telemetry module destructor or via a smart pointer, 
    // but I can't track it down.
}
```

Can you give me a systematic approach to debugging this in a resource-constrained environment? I don't have access to Valgrind on this hardware.

